<p align="right"><b>August 9, 1998</b>
<p><center><h2>Three Organizations take Responsibility for the
Bombing in Nairobi and Dar al-Salam</h2></center>
<p>
<P>Three Islamic Extremist organizations have so far taken responsibility
for the two bombings on Friday August 7<SUP>th</SUP>, 1998, in Nairobi
and Dar al-Salaam. All three are previously unknown names in the Islamic
extremist arena. These names may well be cover names whose purpose is to
mislead investigators. Alternately, they may be aliases used as a consequence
of rivalry between various groups. The three names are “Al-Aqsa Group”
(<I>Jama`at al-Aqsa</I>), The Meccan Group” (<I>Jama`at Makkah</I>), and
“The liberation Army of the Islamic sanctuaries”<I> (Jaysh Tahrir al-Muqaddasat
al-Islamiyyah</I>).

<P>All these claims of responsibility were made via anonymous phone calls
to Arab journalists, characterized by scant detail, so that it is difficult
to identify the exact nature of the organizations or of the callers, beside
the Islamic militant nature.
<P>


